{{Infobox company | name = Ibotta, Inc. | logo = LogoIbottacopyrighted2016.png | type = Private | founded = 2011 | founder = Bryan Leach | hq_location_city = [[Denver, Colorado]] | area_served = United States | key_people = Bryan Leach (CEO), Luke Swanson, Kane McCord, Karsten Voermann, Tim Hannan, [[James H. Clark]] | industry = Technology, [[Coupons]], [[mobile applications]] | services = Cash Back, Brand Discovery, Engagement, Consumer Marketing, Analytics | num_employees = 290+ | num_employees_year = 2016 | homepage = https://www.ibotta.com/ }}
'''Ibotta''' is a [[Denver, Colorado]] based mobile technology company that enables users with its smartphone app to earn cash back on in-store and mobile purchases with receipt and/or purchase verification.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/01/business/economy/cities-where-us-economy-is-thriving.html|title=The Cities on the Sunny Side of the American Economy|last=Cohen|first=Patricia|date=2016-03-31|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-08-10}}</ref>
It was founded by current CEO Bryan Leach,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ibotta.com/company |title=About us |publisher=Ibotta}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2017/06/28/ibotta-expands-downtown-denver/|title=Ibotta expands (again!) by doubling office space in downtown Denver|date=2017-06-28|work=The Denver Post|access-date=2018-05-22|language=en-US}}</ref> for which he was named by [[Ernst & Young]] as a regional Entrepreneur of the Year for 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ey.com/US/en/Newsroom/News-releases/news-ey-announces-winners-for-the-ey-entrepreneur-of-the-year-2015-mountain-desert-award|title=News – EY Announces Winners for the EY Entrepreneur Of The Year® 2015 Mountain Desert Award|website=www.ey.com|accessdate=2016-08-11}}</ref> [[James H. Clark|Jim Clark]] is an investor and board member. As of 2016, Ibotta has received over $73 million in funding.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/09/30/mobile-savings-app-ibotta-scores-40-million/|title=Mobile Savings App Ibotta Scores $40 Million|first=Sarah|last=Perez|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2016/01/14/venture-funding-down-in-colorado-but-firms-still-finding-money/|title=Venture funding down in Colorado but firms still finding money – The Denver Post|accessdate=2016-08-11}}</ref>
The company partners with brands and retailers to offer rebates and discounts on [[Consumer Packaged Goods|consumer packaged goods]], retail purchases, and restaurant dining through a mobile app, similar to traditional [[coupons]] or [[Rebate (marketing)|rebates]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/eladnatanson/2015/07/15/how-major-brands-combine-app-innovation-with-old-fashioned-marketing-principles-to-win-in-mobile/#10be72fc13e6|title=How Major Brands Combine App Innovation With Old-Fashioned Marketing Principles To Win In Mobile|last=Natanson|first=Elad|accessdate=2016-08-10}}</ref><ref name="auto">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/feature/2016-millennials-coupons/|title=Penny-Pinching Millennials Are Keeping the Coupon Alive|website=Bloomberg.com|accessdate=2016-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/learnvest/2016/08/04/8-apps-to-save-you-money-on-supplies-clothes-food-and-more-back-to-school-shopping-gear/#20b48f161b8b|title=8 Apps To Save You Money On Supplies, Clothes, Food And More Back-To-School Shopping Gear|last=LearnVest|accessdate=2016-08-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.adweek.com/news/technology/world-constantly-deleted-apps-mobile-player-uses-cash-keep-folks-coming-back-163025|title=In a World of Constantly Deleted Apps, This Mobile Player Uses Cash to Keep Folks Coming Back|accessdate=2016-08-11}}</ref> Ibotta also has cash back and rebates on alcohol (wine, beer, and spirits) that can be purchased at bars, restaurants, and liquor and grocery stores.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2016/03/02/free-beer-budweiser-app/|title=Free Beer! There's an App for That|date=2016-03-02|website=Fortune|accessdate=2016-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/how-to-save-on-holiday-spirits-wine-and-beer-2015-12-29|title=How to save on holiday spirits, wine and beer|last=Pavini|first=Jeanette|accessdate=2016-08-11}}</ref> Ibotta users must be of legal drinking age, even if the consumer has no intention of purchasing beer or wine, or if they patronize a business that does not sell such items.
The app is available on both iOS and Android devices and is available only in the United States as of October 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mobilestrategies360.com/2015/10/01/mobile-shopping-app-ibotta-raises-40-million|title=Mobile shopping app Ibotta raises $40 million|last=Evans|first=Katie|accessdate=2016-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2015/09/28/ibotta-plans-to-hire-200-300-triple-denver-office-space-2/|title=Ibotta plans to hire 200-300, triple Denver office space – The Denver Post|accessdate=2016-08-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/09/30/mobile-savings-app-ibotta-scores-40-million/|title=Mobile Savings App Ibotta Scores $40 Million|last=Perez|first=Sarah|website=TechCrunch|accessdate=2016-08-10}}</ref><ref name="auto"/> Ibotta claims to work at over 500,000 locations within the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://appinformers.com/2015/10/ibotta-gets-40-million-funding-grow-business/|title=Ibotta Gets $40 Million in Funding – AppInformers.com|date=2015-10-01|language=en-US|accessdate=2016-08-11}}</ref>
