[[File:Jason Kuchel, Chief Executive, South Australian Chamber of Mines and Energy (2015).jpg|alt=Jason Kuchel|thumb|Jason Kuchel]] The '''Minerals and Energy Advisory Council''' is an entity which represents the interests of resources and energy companies to the Government of South Australia. It was formed in 2015 in a merger of the [[Resources Industry Development Board]] and the [[Resources & Energy Sector Infrastructure Council|Resources and Energy Sector Infrastructure Council]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.minerals.statedevelopment.sa.gov.au/partnerships/minerals_and_energy_advisory_council_MEAC|title=Minerals and Energy Advisory Council (MEAC)|last=|first=|website=www.minerals.statedevelopment.sa.gov.au|access-date=2016-05-23}}</ref> It is in a partnership with the [[Olympic Dam Task Force]]. In 2016, the MEAC discussed the future use of small modular nuclear reactors in South Australia and the need to legalise their deployment. The MEAC also prepared a report on the findings of the [[Nuclear Fuel Cycle Royal Commission]] to present to Minister [[Tom Koutsantonis|Tom Koutantonis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://minerals.statedevelopment.sa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0008/278828/MEAC_Minutes_30March2016_.pdf|title=Minerals and Energy Advisory Council - Meeting Minutes 30 March 2016|last=|first=|date=2016-06-22|website=|publisher=Government of South Australia|access-date=2016-07-13}}</ref>
