{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}} {{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = | name = William Archibald Cadell | honorific_suffix = | image = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 1708<!-- {{Birth date|df=yes|1708|MM|DD}} --> | birth_place = | death_date = 1777<!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|1777|MM|DD|1708|MM|DD}}--> | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline}} --> | monuments = | residence = [[Cockenzie]], [[Scotland]] | nationality = | other_names = | education = | alma_mater = | occupation = Industrialist | years_active = | employer = | organization = | agent = | known_for = Founder of [[Carron Iron Works]] | notable_works = | home_town = | religion = | spouse = | children = | parents = | relatives = [[Henry Cadell]] (great, great grandson) }}
'''William Archibald Cadell''' of [[Cockenzie]] (1708–1777) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] industrialist, one of the pioneers of the industrial revolution on the [[Firth of Forth]]. He was a member of a merchant family involved in the import of iron from Russia and Sweden.
He and his son, also William (baptised 1737, died 1819<ref name="ODNB">R. H. Campbell, ‘Garbett, Samuel (1717–1803)’, Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/40491, accessed 29 July 2012]</ref>), were founders with [[Samuel Garbett]] and [[John Roebuck]], of the [[Carron Iron Works]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/legacies/work/scotland/central_and_fife/article_1.shtml|title=Carron: Scotland's Forge|publisher=BBC|accessdate=6 March 2010}}</ref> in 1759, originally known as Roebuck, Garbett & Cadells.
His daughter Christian Cadell married Thomas Edington (1742-1811) who became joint proprietor at Cramond Iron Works before establishing his own independent company in [[Glasgow]] in 1797: Thomas Edington & Son. Their grandson was the geologist [[Thomas Edington]] [[FRSE]] (1814-1859).<ref>Graces Guide: Thomas Edington & Son</ref>
His great, great grandson was the geologist [[Henry Cadell]].
